			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1683">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Poe Ballantine paints a brilliant and deeply disturbing portrait of the modern plague of methamphetamines [&ldquo;<a href="/article/3682">Methamphetamine for Dummies</a>,&rdquo; July 2007]. His message of despair is true for many other illusions that the material world offers the unwary. There are plenty of dead-end roads available; all seem to lead to sun-filled days but ultimately end in suffering and loss. Like drug addicts, we strive for comfort and pleasure, and we exploit each other to get it. Our garages and attics are full of things cast aside, and broken relationships abound. The fortunate among us discover that the real path to happiness lies in service. Only by giving of ourselves can we become fully human.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Troy Criscuolo<br>San Luis Obispo, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1684">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>&ldquo;Methamphetamine for Dummies&rdquo; hit home with me, literally. I am from San Diego, where the events of the essay took place, and I have seen firsthand the horrible consequences of meth addiction. One time, while working at a local market, I sold a Snickers bar to a known &ldquo;tweaker.&rdquo; After he left the store, I watched through the window as he bit into the candy bar and made a confused face. At first I thought the candy had gone stale. Then he looked over at me and held the bar up for my inspection. Two of his teeth were embedded in it. He just smiled, shrugged, and went about his day.</p>

<p>I hope that more people will read Ballantine&rsquo;s essay before they fall into this trap. Meth will cost them everything: their health, their dreams, their relationships, their money &mdash; everything. All you ever hope to achieve will go straight up your nose.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Bill Finley<br>San Diego, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

